The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 UBI recast dossier to be ready by March

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 UBI chairman and managing director Parkash Singh (right) in Calcutta on Tuesday. Picture by Kishor Roy Chowdhury

 Calcutta, Feb. 22: National Institute of Banking Management (NIBM) will submit a restructuring report on United Bank of India (UBI) by March end.

 The report will address key issues like implementation of Basel-II accord and the organisational changes related to it. It will also advise on core banking solutions and the first public issue.

 ?We are expecting a net profit of Rs 200 crore this fiscal. Our advances have grown by 20 per cent and our target is to grow it by 22 per cent next fiscal. We need the restructuring report so that we can bring in necessary changes required for our growth,? said Parkash Singh, chairman and managing director of United Bank of India.

 The bank will float its initial public offer in 2006-07 after wiping out its accumulated losses.

 At present, the bank has an accumulated loss of Rs 475 crore. ?We plan to completely wipe it out in 2005-06,? said K. N. Prithviraj, executive director of UBI. The bank has received an approval from the Reserve Bank of India to open its first representative office in Bangladesh. The rep office will be opened in Dhaka within a year?s time. 

 UBI is also exploring the possibilities of opening rep offices in countries like Singapore, China, Malaysia and Hong Kong.

 This fiscal, the bank?s retail portfolio has touched Rs 1,760 crore. The total advances in 2004-05 is expected to touch a figure of Rs 3,000 crore. ?Our aim is to achieve Rs 4,000 crore in advances in 2005-06,? Singh added. The bank has made a recovery of Rs 85 crore, which includes a cash recovery of Rs 70 crore. It hopes to bring down bad assets to 2 per cent in 2004-05.

 The bank has tied up with Bajaj Allianz General Insurance for promotion of non-life general insurance products. 




